  "Appear to have two letters": [
   {
    "text": "Sometimes, we find words that only appear to have two recognizable letters, like מֵת, (",
    "type": "text"
   },
   {
    "type": "italics",
    "tokens": [
     {
      "text": "meis",
      "type": "text"
     }
    ]
   },
   {
    "text": ", “he is dying.”) ",
    "type": "text"
   },
   {
    "topLevelNodes": [
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "Some consider the word מֵת to come from a two-letter shoresh “מת”",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     },
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "Some consider מֵת to come from a shoresh “מות,” whose “weak middle letter” gets hidden in certain conjugations. (Examples of “weak” letters are י,‎ ו and ה.)",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     },
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "Either way, it is just a disagreement about what to call things, not over the spelling of any actual word.",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     },
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "This site generally uses three letter shorushim like “מות” to keep things consistent, but either system is correct.",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     }
    ],
    "type": "outline"
   }
  ],
  "Corollaries in English": [
   {
    "text": "In English, you often have a linguistic root like “mem” which is used to produce a series of related words like “memory,” “memorize,” or “memorable.” Shorushim are a similar concept, except they are a bit more formal than in English, because there are fixed rules for how many letters they can be, and how they get turned into words.",
    "type": "text"
   }
  ],
  "Used to produce words": [
   {
    "text": "A shoresh is called a “root” because many words derive from one shoresh. ",
    "type": "text"
   },
   {
    "topLevelNodes": [
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "A shoresh has a general meaning is used to generate many words with more specific meanings.",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     },
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "For example, the shoresh אכל “eating” can be plugged into a particular verb pattern to generate the verb לְהַאֲכִיל, ",
        "type": "text"
       },
       {
        "type": "italics",
        "tokens": [
         {
          "text": "leha’achil",
          "type": "text"
         }
        ]
       },
       {
        "text": ", “to feed.”",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     },
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "(For advanced readers, these patterns are called ",
        "type": "text"
       },
       {
        "text": "binyanim",
        "type": "global",
        "tokens": [
         {
          "text": "binyanim",
          "type": "text"
